{{en-noun}}

# An [[illuminating]] [[realization]] or [[discovery]], often resulting in a personal feeling of [[elation]], [[awe]], or [[wonder]].
#: {{syn|en|aha moment|enlightenment|nirvana|satori}}
#: {{ux|en|It came to her in an '''epiphany''' what her life's work was to be.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Lipstick Traces|author={{w|Greil Marcus}}|year_published=2009|year=1989|publisher=Faber & Faber|passage=Instead of examining institutions and classes, structures of economic production and social control, one had to think about “moments”—moments of love, hate, poetry, frustration, action, surrender, delight, humiliation, justice, cruelty, resignation, surprise, disgust, resentment, self-loathing, pity, fury, peace of mind—those tiny '''epiphanies''', Lefebvre said, in which the absolute possibilities and temporal limits of anyone's existence were revealed.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Chris Hadfield|authorlink=Chris Hadfield|title=An Astronaut's Guide to Life on Earth|year=2013|publisher=Pan Macmillan|chapter=11|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=ymqqXuGFL9sC&pg=PP240&dq=%22had+an+epiphany%22&hl=&cd=17&source=gbs_api#v=onepage&q&f=false|isbn=978-1-4472-5712-7|passage=But after spending most of my pocket money to get those developed, I had an '''epiphany''': I was never going to be a professional photographer. My pictures were god-awful. I put the camera away.}}
